nditions affecting the cervical spine or the lung apex, like Pancoast's syndrome.","dimension":2,"group":3,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.026392,0.048963,0.068932,0.083995,0.096796,0.1046,0.11081,0.11231,0.10752,0.098546,0.077823,0.063315],"unified_progress":[0.0286,0.057815,0.080185,0.095389,0.10109,0.10876,0.10887,0.10515,0.099464,0.091817,0.071627,0.051239]},{"section":11,"text":"Pancoast's tumor is a type of lung cancer, typically located in the superior pulmonary sulcus, and it can cause Horner's syndrome because it affects the brachial plexus.","dimension":2,"group":3,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.01942,0.039909,0.059396,0.074664,0.095446,0.10812,0.11497,0.12193,0.11914,0.1007,0.079724,0.066573],"unified_progress":[0.02438,0.052642,0.076946,0.094175,0.10164,0.11364,0.11284,0.10834,0.10132,0.092257,0.070564,0.051259]},{"section":12,"text":"The pain from Pancoast's tumor is usually in the left upper limb, which matches the patient's symptoms of left upper limb pain, paraesthesia, and weakness.","dimension":9,"group":5,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.044387,0.066957,0.070282,0.077222,0.082543,0.089227,0.095793,0.099201,0.099364,0.094063,0.090363,0.090598],"unified_progress":[0.049659,0.069176,0.0753,0.082865,0.088352,0.095841,0.094661,0.097955,0.094811,0.090581,0.083818,0.076982]},{"section":13,"text":"The weight loss, cough, and hemoptysis also align with a lung malignancy.","dimension":4,"group":0,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.044379,0.061862,0.070844,0.076627,0.0794,0.083589,0.087898,0.090945,0.093221,0.09671,0.10171,0.11281],"unified_progress":[0.045228,0.061446,0.068889,0.075508,0.080822,0.086684,0.088054,0.094044,0.095792,0.096434,0.10127,0.10583]},{"section":14,"text":"So putting it all together, the combination of smoking history, respiratory symptoms, and the development of Horner's syndrome points towards a Pancoast's tumor.","dimension":4,"group":0,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.019093,0.033422,0.